\begin_layout Standard
As with all true origin stories, we begin with my mother.
 My mom raised me on her own (with a few abusive relationships here and
 there), and had her own successful business.
 Unfortunately, two months after I had turned 18, my mother took her own
 life, and I've been on my own ever since.
 Despite all these challenges growing up, one thing has always kept me going:
 learning.
 My mother used to tell a story about me in second grade to brag at family
 reunions.
 When I was in second grade, I caught the nickname "Dr.
 Knox" from the teachers.
 I was well known for asking complicated questions and trying to find where
 things broke down.
 Ever since then, I've vowed to make that nickname it a reality.
 For me, graduate school is the next step in learning more about the world
 around us.
 In a way, I feel as though I need to pursue graduate school even more now
 that I've seen just how much I don't know.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As for choosing to stay at Purdue specifically: I would be lying if I didn't
 attribute some of the blame to the gorgeous campus and the continued developmen
ts I've seen throughout the years.
 I honestly feel as though I have a vested interest in the community here,
 and I would love to continue my academic studies in the community I've
 come to adore so much.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After graduate school, I want to pursue computational physics, likely in
 the private sector.
 I love taking immensely complex problems, describing them symbolically
 and/or programatically, and utilizing computational/numerical methods to
 solve them to arbitrary precision.
 Another theory I have is that I just enjoy the cool simulations and software,
 but the former sounds better on paper.
 I would definitely consider a governmental or public job with the same
 duties, provided theres at least a little variablility in the types of
 jobs/tasks/etc.
 we recieve.
\end_layout

